{{Other uses|Porus (disambiguation)}}
There are related [[mythology|mythological]] figures named '''Porus''' or '''Poros''' ({{lang-grc|Πόρος}} "resource" or "plenty") in [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] [[classical literature]].
In [[Plato]]'s ''[[Symposium (Plato)|Symposium]]'', Porus was the personification of resourcefulness or expediency.<ref>{{cite book|first= Robert|last=Flacelière|date=2008|title=A Literary History of Greece|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DTiaFeEaCgEC&dq|pages=275-276|isbn=0202362957}}</ref> He was seduced by [[Penia]] (poverty) while drunk on more than his fill of nectar at [[Aphrodite]]'s birthday. Penia gave birth to [[Eros (god)|Eros]] (love) from their union. Porus was the son of [[Metis (mythology)|Metis]]. According to the character Diotima, Eros is forever in need because of his mother, but forever pursuing because of his father.<ref>{{cite book|first=Julius|last=Evola|date=1991|title=Eros and the Mysteries of Love|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zlAX8pSUHSkC&pg|pages=57-59|isbn=0892813156}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book|first=Mark|last=Morford||date=1999|title=Classical Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ecGXcMRAPXcC&dq|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=133-134|isbn=0195143388}}</ref>
This figure exists in [[Roman mythology]] as well and is known as [[Pomona (mythology)|Pomona]],{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} in which Porus is the [[personification]] of [[:wikt:abundance|abundance]]. He is the brother of Athena.
